00:35:50.280 --> 00:35:54.280
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen. I'm chatting with the economist Ajay Shah about

00:35:54.280 --> 00:35:58.120
[Amit Varma]: zombie firms. You should really make a horror film on this. If Bollywood kind of took this up,

00:35:58.120 --> 00:36:04.680
[Amit Varma]: that would be great. You know, part of your analysis of zombie firms and all the pieces

00:36:04.680 --> 00:36:10.920
[Amit Varma]: that you've written on it involves the state, the government not understanding how prices work

00:36:10.920 --> 00:36:15.560
[Amit Varma]: fundamentally. Tell me a little bit about that. I mean, I've had episodes in the past on how

00:36:15.560 --> 00:36:18.120
[Amit Varma]: damaging price controls and all of that. Just take me through.

00:36:19.320 --> 00:36:26.440
[Guest]: So I feel that a child can understand the price system. And yet, so many people seem to not

00:36:26.440 --> 00:36:31.080
[Guest]: particularly think about the price system. It's it's just it's a great recipe for understanding

00:36:31.080 --> 00:36:37.320
[Guest]: the world. It's like an invisible formula that is running the world. And it's a secret that only a

00:36:37.320 --> 00:36:44.520
[Guest]: few people have. So let me let me talk a bit about how some of these things work. And at once,

00:36:44.520 --> 00:36:48.920
[Guest]: these are trivial observations. And yet they're interesting and powerful observations. So let's

00:36:48.920 --> 00:36:56.680
[Guest]: start at planes once again. So we had some of these Boeing 737 MAX planes being grounded because

00:36:56.680 --> 00:37:03.960
[Guest]: of safety concerns. And at about the same time, we had a disruption in jet airways. So the supply

00:37:03.960 --> 00:37:08.440
[Guest]: of planes, the supply of seats on planes was adversely affected.

00:37:08.440 --> 00:37:10.280
[Amit Varma]: This is what economists would call a supply shock.

00:37:10.280 --> 00:37:17.640
[Guest]: It was a supply shock. Now, the fundamental nature of the price system is that the price

00:37:17.640 --> 00:37:23.960
[Guest]: moves to equate supply and demand. OK, so there is a market and that market is not clearing that

00:37:23.960 --> 00:37:28.600
[Guest]: there are 100 people trying to buy seats, but there are only 80 seats. There's a mismatch that

00:37:28.600 --> 00:37:35.880
[Guest]: doesn't work. How the price system deals with it is that prices go up until 20 guys walk away.

00:37:35.880 --> 00:37:42.440
[Guest]: OK, so the price system rations out the limited seats that are available. So let's visualize that

00:37:42.440 --> 00:37:47.960
[Guest]: there's a Bombay Delhi ticket, which was ordinarily some 7000 rupees. And now there's a shortage of

00:37:47.960 --> 00:37:53.720
[Guest]: supply. So the price system. So let's just fix numbers. There are 100 people trying to buy seats

00:37:53.720 --> 00:37:57.640
[Guest]: and there are only 80 available. So think of the price system as running an auction.

00:37:57.640 --> 00:38:03.160
[Guest]: It says, no, instead of 7000, I'm going to go to 7500. Some people in the room drop out and they

00:38:03.160 --> 00:38:09.400
[Guest]: say, OK, at 7500, I'm not going to fly. Does that get you to 20 people dropping out? If not, let's

00:38:09.400 --> 00:38:13.960
[Guest]: go to 8000 rupees for the ticket and you keep raising the price until there are only 80 guys

00:38:13.960 --> 00:38:20.600
[Guest]: left. OK, that's the imaginary anthropomorphized price system. That's what the price system does.

00:38:21.640 --> 00:38:26.440
[Guest]: Now you go one deeper into that and you say, how much do you think I'd have to raise plane

00:38:26.440 --> 00:38:33.880
[Guest]: tickets to get maybe 5% or 10% of the flyers to drop out? And you know what? Not a lot.

00:38:33.880 --> 00:38:40.680
[Guest]: Because for many people in India, flying is a choice. You may choose to not fly. You may choose

00:38:40.680 --> 00:38:46.760
[Guest]: to use a train. You may choose to use a Volvo bus. So many people are on that borderline. Flying is

00:38:46.760 --> 00:38:52.680
[Guest]: not some critical, essential thing. It's still something that we have a discretionary expenditure

00:38:52.680 --> 00:38:57.720
[Guest]: on flying. So my prediction would be that a relatively modest movement in the price

00:38:58.280 --> 00:39:03.320
[Guest]: would work to clear supply and demand. And so it's not a big disruption. There's no great

00:39:03.320 --> 00:39:09.400
[Guest]: change in prices that occurs. It's nice. There's a 5-10% move in the prices. That's great for the

00:39:09.400 --> 00:39:14.440
[Guest]: profitability of Indigo and Go Air and SpiceJet and all that. This is the time they deserve to

00:39:14.440 --> 00:39:18.920
[Guest]: make money. Once again, there are people who will call this profiteering. And I say, look,

00:39:18.920 --> 00:39:25.720
[Guest]: this is the joy that these firms get in return for the long slog of fighting it out while Air

00:39:25.720 --> 00:39:30.440
[Guest]: India was underpricing tickets and Jet Airways was there. And in those years, the other airlines

00:39:30.440 --> 00:39:36.760
[Guest]: did badly. And this is the moment when you make money, because when the other guys exit is your

00:39:36.760 --> 00:39:41.720
[Guest]: great opportunity to make money. We should not grudge them. This time, we should not be getting

00:39:41.720 --> 00:39:47.560
[Guest]: angry at the fact that they are gouging customers or they are profiteering. This is markets. This is

00:39:47.560 --> 00:39:53.800
[Guest]: the normal movement of the price system. If I may take an example from an unrelated industry,

00:39:53.800 --> 00:40:01.800
[Guest]: let's consider wheat. Now, wheat is a very cheap grain and wheat is a staple. And most of us don't

00:40:01.800 --> 00:40:07.640
[Guest]: even know the price of wheat that goes into the chapati that we eat, which means that if there

00:40:07.640 --> 00:40:12.440
[Guest]: was a supply shock, so imagine there was a drought, there was a failure of the Rabi crop in Punjab and

00:40:12.440 --> 00:40:17.800
[Guest]: Haryana. Now, there is a problem. There is not enough wheat. So if the price of wheat goes up

00:40:17.800 --> 00:40:23.720
[Guest]: by 5% or 10%, it would not work to clear supply and demand. You would need a large movement in

00:40:23.720 --> 00:40:28.600
[Guest]: the price of wheat to make people change their behavior, to shift away from wheat to eating rice,

00:40:28.600 --> 00:40:33.240
[Guest]: to eating bajra, whatever. There would be adjustments. But for many people, you would

00:40:33.240 --> 00:40:38.280
[Guest]: need a large movement in the price of wheat to elicit a change in behavior. And the term economists

00:40:38.280 --> 00:40:42.680
[Amit Varma]: use for this is demand elasticity. So the demand elasticity of the wheat consumer is different to

00:40:42.680 --> 00:40:48.520
[Guest]: the airline flyer. Exactly. So I was particularly comfortable at the prospect of a supply shock in

00:40:48.520 --> 00:40:54.760
[Guest]: airlines, because our elementary intuition into the kind of behavior of flyers is that people are

00:40:54.760 --> 00:40:58.920
[Guest]: highly sensitive to price. People are always conscious of what they're spending when they

00:40:58.920 --> 00:41:04.440
[Guest]: buy a plane ticket. So you would expect a given supply disruption to get tidied over with a

00:41:04.440 --> 00:41:08.360
[Guest]: relatively modest movement in the price. Whereas in something like wheat, you would get large

00:41:08.360 --> 00:41:13.080
[Guest]: movements in the price. Once again, we shouldn't get angry about these movements. This is the

00:41:13.080 --> 00:41:17.560
[Amit Varma]: price system. This is what prices do. And what a lot of people demand is that, you know, if the

00:41:17.560 --> 00:41:21.400
[Amit Varma]: price of something, especially something essential goes too high, they say no, no, the government

00:41:21.400 --> 00:41:25.000
[Amit Varma]: should control it. But, you know, I've had in I've had different episodes in price controls,

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:31.560
[Amit Varma]: including an Uber. So I'll just kind of illustrate that with an example of two things that, you know,

00:41:31.560 --> 00:41:37.480
[Amit Varma]: letting the price adjust does one is let's say that there are 100 potential Uber customers at

00:41:37.480 --> 00:41:42.120
[Amit Varma]: a given point in time who want a taxi, but there are only 50 taxis available. Now, if you fix the

00:41:42.120 --> 00:41:47.800
[Amit Varma]: price, what happens is that is first come first serve, the first 50 people get it, the other 50

00:41:47.800 --> 00:41:52.280
[Amit Varma]: are simply stranded. Now, you could be someone who has an urgent need, maybe you need to take your

00:41:52.280 --> 00:41:56.360
[Amit Varma]: aging father to the hospital, maybe you need to catch a flight, you would be willing to pay much

00:41:56.360 --> 00:42:01.240
[Amit Varma]: more, but you're stranded. And some of the people who happen to get the taxis, the lucky 50 could

00:42:01.240 --> 00:42:05.320
[Amit Varma]: just be going out for an errand or you know, they could easily walk or take a bus or do something

00:42:05.320 --> 00:42:10.360
[Amit Varma]: else is trivial, or they could just sit at home and watch Netflix. And they get it instead.

00:42:10.360 --> 00:42:15.560
[Amit Varma]: Whereas if you allowed the price to adjust, two important things would happen. One is that it

00:42:15.560 --> 00:42:20.440
[Amit Varma]: would be allocated depending on how desperately someone wanted it because a guy who has to go to

00:42:20.440 --> 00:42:24.280
[Amit Varma]: the airport, the guy who has to take his dad to the hospital, they'd be willing to pay more.

00:42:24.280 --> 00:42:27.800
[Amit Varma]: And someone whose need might be trivial, who can just you know, it's a five minute drive,

00:42:27.800 --> 00:42:34.520
[Amit Varma]: he can take an auto or walk would do that. So the price system effectively sort of sorts those guys

00:42:34.520 --> 00:42:38.120
[Amit Varma]: out. The second and the more important thing that it does, which even applies to airlines or

00:42:38.120 --> 00:42:43.960
[Amit Varma]: anything is that it sends information, it sends information to idle Uber drivers that listen,

00:42:43.960 --> 00:42:49.000
[Amit Varma]: there is a profit to be made. And for their self interest to get into the market to fulfill the

00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:55.160
[Amit Varma]: needs of the guys who would otherwise be stranded. And this information on both ends to both the

00:42:55.160 --> 00:43:00.680
[Amit Varma]: buyer and the seller so that they can adjust is something that I think is unintuitive and unseen.

00:43:00.680 --> 00:43:04.840
[Amit Varma]: And people don't often get it that if you fix the price, you will have scarcity,

00:43:04.840 --> 00:43:09.240
[Amit Varma]: it will be first come first serve. And a price system is beautiful, not just in the short term

00:43:09.240 --> 00:43:15.880
[Amit Varma]: way of letting people get what they need based on their how urgent the requirement is, but also in a

00:43:15.880 --> 00:43:21.240
[Amit Varma]: long term way of fixing that supply demand shortfall. So I want to talk about two things.

00:43:21.240 --> 00:43:26.840
[Guest]: If I may do this in reverse order, I'll come to what you just said in a moment. So I'm very happy

00:43:26.840 --> 00:43:33.480
[Guest]: you brought up Uber, because there is something fundamental and profound about the gig economy.

00:43:33.480 --> 00:43:41.880
[Guest]: And it fits beautifully in our intuition about how markets work. There was a paper done by people at

00:43:41.880 --> 00:43:46.760
[Guest]: the Center for Civil Society, which did some things that were quite interesting and an eye

00:43:46.760 --> 00:43:55.160
[Guest]: opener to me personally. This was about Airbnb. And they found that one of the features of Airbnb

00:43:56.120 --> 00:44:02.280
[Guest]: accommodations that users valued the most was a kitchenette. And it turns out that this is

00:44:02.280 --> 00:44:08.600
[Guest]: something quite difficult to do within the normal government regulatory system. So the gig economy

00:44:08.600 --> 00:44:12.920
[Guest]: is particularly good at discovering products and features in its own way that traditional

00:44:12.920 --> 00:44:18.280
[Guest]: regulatory structures might fumble at. And I think that's an important lesson to all of us that

00:44:18.840 --> 00:44:24.440
[Guest]: let that self-organizing system work and discover solutions as opposed to using regulation.

00:44:24.440 --> 00:44:30.200
[Guest]: That said, there is a role for regulation. And let me talk about your example. So first,

00:44:30.200 --> 00:44:35.720
[Guest]: I agree with everything you said, but now let me bring the cautionary note about the problem and

00:44:35.720 --> 00:44:42.360
[Guest]: how we worry about it. The technical phrase we use in the field of the economics of public policy

00:44:42.360 --> 00:44:49.400
[Guest]: is market failure. A market failure is a situation in which the self-organizing system,

00:44:49.400 --> 00:44:55.160
[Guest]: the individual decentralized decisions by all of us does not work so well, where something goes

00:44:55.160 --> 00:44:59.720
[Guest]: wrong. And there are four categories of market failures. And the first of them and the most

00:44:59.720 --> 00:45:05.080
[Guest]: important of them in one way is a monopoly. So when there's market power, when somebody's a

00:45:05.080 --> 00:45:09.720
[Guest]: monopolist, things don't work so well. The monopolist will gouge the consumer. The monopolist

00:45:09.720 --> 00:45:16.040
[Guest]: will artificially depress production and will extract consumer surplus. So nobody likes a

00:45:16.040 --> 00:45:21.320
[Guest]: monopoly. And in a way, a lot of what we do in public policy is designed to combat these

00:45:21.320 --> 00:45:28.520
[Guest]: monopolies. Now, when you go back to the beginning of the taxi industry, which is now like 70, 80

00:45:28.520 --> 00:45:34.440
[Guest]: years old all over the world, the situation that was on the mind of everybody was like this, that

00:45:35.480 --> 00:45:39.960
[Guest]: there is one taxi cab on a street and you are one consumer on the street and you go up to the taxi

00:45:39.960 --> 00:45:46.200
[Guest]: cab and say, will you go there? And the guy realizes that you're desperate and he's a monopoly

00:45:46.200 --> 00:45:53.080
[Guest]: in that brief moment and he can basically charge anything. So the regulation of taxi fares came

00:45:53.080 --> 00:45:59.640
[Guest]: out of that problem. That in that situation, the bargaining power is entirely asymmetric. And when

00:45:59.640 --> 00:46:04.680
[Guest]: there is only one taxi cab on the pavement, that person gets the ability to charge almost anything.

00:46:04.680 --> 00:46:08.920
[Amit Varma]: And also if I may interrupt, the problem in India is that the supply of those taxi cabs is also

00:46:08.920 --> 00:46:12.520
[Amit Varma]: controlled by the government because there are only limited licenses they give out. So that,

00:46:12.520 --> 00:46:13.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, furthers the scarcity.

00:46:13.960 --> 00:46:17.560
[Guest]: Yeah. Same as the New York taxi cabs, which are artificially restricted.

00:46:17.560 --> 00:46:23.080
[Guest]: Yeah. But I just want to focus on that point that there is market failure in this problem.

00:46:23.080 --> 00:46:30.360
[Guest]: And that is why there is regulation of taxi cabs. Now, in the limit, the Uber surge pricing

00:46:30.360 --> 00:46:37.880
[Guest]: can potentially collapse into that same problem. That in the central systems, Uber sees that many

00:46:37.880 --> 00:46:43.960
[Guest]: customers are walking on a street with its app open. So Uber has a unique ability to see where

00:46:43.960 --> 00:46:48.840
[Guest]: its users are. And it knows that on that street, there are only three taxi cabs. So you've got a

00:46:48.840 --> 00:46:55.240
[Guest]: little monopoly. And now why not charge the moon for that? So everything you said is correct, that

00:46:55.880 --> 00:47:02.200
[Guest]: the price will ration out the users and will allocate the scarce goods to the people who

00:47:02.200 --> 00:47:07.720
[Guest]: want it the most. The high price will attract more consumers. But we do have a regulatory

00:47:07.720 --> 00:47:13.720
[Guest]: problem, which is that it is perfectly feasible for Uber to turn into just a classic 19th century

00:47:13.720 --> 00:47:18.600
[Guest]: fear of a monopolist. And I don't have an answer for how you would solve this problem. But I just

00:47:18.600 --> 00:47:24.520
[Guest]: want to say that good economists do worry about Uber surge pricing as well. So I have like three

00:47:24.520 --> 00:47:29.880
[Amit Varma]: responses to this. One is, of course, like, you know, when we see a market failure, we often think

00:47:29.880 --> 00:47:34.200
[Amit Varma]: of the government has to step in. But I think as you know, public choice theory would tell you that

00:47:34.200 --> 00:47:38.760
[Amit Varma]: government failure is far more endemic and in a sense, I would argue even inevitable because of

00:47:38.760 --> 00:47:43.240
[Amit Varma]: the way the incentives are aligned. But leaving that broader point aside, you know, when you point

00:47:43.240 --> 00:47:47.960
[Amit Varma]: out about, you know, your traditional Kali Pili taxi, how it's a monopoly for a moment when you

00:47:47.960 --> 00:47:51.800
[Amit Varma]: want to go somewhere and he can charge whatever he wants. I don't know if I'd call it a market

00:47:51.800 --> 00:47:56.360
[Amit Varma]: failure, because the reason that scarcity exists and that monopoly exists for the moment is because

00:47:57.080 --> 00:48:00.200
[Amit Varma]: the state is interfering in the, you know, market entry.

00:48:00.840 --> 00:48:04.600
[Guest]: Even if entry were open, there will always be these dumb luck situations,

00:48:04.600 --> 00:48:11.800
[Guest]: where, so to use a London analogy, it starts raining. Then suddenly, there is a surge of users

00:48:11.800 --> 00:48:17.720
[Guest]: of taxis, and there will be a street where there will be two, three taxis. And so there's always a

00:48:17.720 --> 00:48:21.240
[Amit Varma]: little lag, the market takes time to adjust, would you call that a market failure per se,

00:48:21.240 --> 00:48:28.520
[Guest]: it would be a market failure if it persists. So if there is a monopoly, where within hundreds of

00:48:28.520 --> 00:48:33.000
[Guest]: meters of walking distance, I really am down to only one or two producers, and they can essentially

00:48:33.000 --> 00:48:38.840
[Amit Varma]: charge me very high prices, I would call that market power. And my third point is that, you

00:48:38.840 --> 00:48:43.160
[Amit Varma]: know, the big issue with a monopoly, of course, is that they can charge high prices and expect

00:48:43.160 --> 00:48:48.040
[Amit Varma]: consumers and so on. And competition keeps prices low and all of that. But a lot of the modern

00:48:48.040 --> 00:48:53.880
[Amit Varma]: monopolies, monopolies, quote, unquote, that people tend to worry about, like an Amazon,

00:48:53.880 --> 00:49:00.120
[Amit Varma]: like a Facebook, like even an Uber, are actually not doing that. You know, even if they control

00:49:00.120 --> 00:49:03.720
[Amit Varma]: the market, you see that the prices are very low, and the consumers are benefiting massively,

00:49:03.720 --> 00:49:07.400
[Guest]: like from Amazon, for example. Well, you have to be cautious about that.

00:49:07.400 --> 00:49:13.320
[Guest]: There is a very plausible scenario that a firm like Amazon or a firm like Uber

00:49:14.120 --> 00:49:19.160
[Guest]: becomes a monopoly at first with very low prices, drives off the competitors. Then after that,

00:49:19.160 --> 00:49:24.120
[Guest]: you've got a network effect that the only game in town is Amazon or the only game in town is Uber,

00:49:24.120 --> 00:49:28.760
[Guest]: and then they would raise prices. So we should look this gift cards in the mouth.

00:49:28.760 --> 00:49:31.880
[Amit Varma]: But if that happens, surely then other entrants will come in.

00:49:31.880 --> 00:49:35.640
[Guest]: By that time, some of these games will be locked up because their network effects. So

00:49:35.640 --> 00:49:41.960
[Guest]: the key network effect in these platform economies, like Uber, is that if I'm a driver,

00:49:41.960 --> 00:49:46.680
[Guest]: and I switch on the Uber app, I've got an order flow coming into that. And if I'm a customer,

00:49:46.680 --> 00:49:51.080
[Guest]: and I open the Uber app, I will find more taxis. Once you've created this network effect,

00:49:51.080 --> 00:49:54.120
[Guest]: then both sides tend to come to that platform because they don't have a choice.

00:49:54.120 --> 00:49:58.520
[Guest]: And that platform can charge supernormal pricing. So there are genuine concerns about these

00:49:58.520 --> 00:50:03.640
[Guest]: markets. I am not quick to say we know solutions. But I think we know enough to be concerned.

00:50:03.640 --> 00:50:07.560
[Amit Varma]: Fair enough. I mean, as of now, I see Uber and Ola and even your, you know,

00:50:07.560 --> 00:50:11.640
[Amit Varma]: Kalipili is playing outside and there's always video conferencing. So why do you even need to go

00:50:11.640 --> 00:50:18.520
[Amit Varma]: anywhere? But I'm kidding. Right. So, so to kind of get back to one of the sort of interesting

00:50:18.520 --> 00:50:23.000
[Amit Varma]: points you made is that if not for state interference, the different ways in which

00:50:24.360 --> 00:50:28.280
[Amit Varma]: the state keeps zombie firms alive or zombie banks keep zombie firms alive, not just in the

00:50:28.280 --> 00:50:32.200
[Amit Varma]: public sector, but the private sector. And in fact, I should ask you to elaborate on that,

00:50:32.200 --> 00:50:37.000
[Amit Varma]: which I will. But one of the effects of that is that downturns are longer that if creative

00:50:37.000 --> 00:50:41.640
[Amit Varma]: destruction is allowed, downturns would be much shorter and you give specific examples of that.

00:50:41.640 --> 00:50:47.640
[Guest]: Can you take me through that? So that the great economist Karl Marx taught us that it is in the

00:50:47.640 --> 00:50:52.520
[Guest]: nature of the market economy that there are booms and busts. Okay, so there are periods of exuberance

00:50:52.520 --> 00:50:59.560
[Guest]: and a great deal of investment. And then the competition hots up and margins go down and

00:50:59.560 --> 00:51:05.880
[Guest]: some firms get into trouble. We in India have lived this twice in the period after the early

00:51:05.880 --> 00:51:13.080
[Guest]: nineties. So let me tell the grand Indian story. The grand Indian story is that in from 93, 94,

00:51:13.080 --> 00:51:19.000
[Guest]: 95, 96, we had investment boom and a great deal of entry took place. So new firms were born,

00:51:19.000 --> 00:51:25.480
[Guest]: new capacities were built. By 97, 98, 99, the world started becoming difficult and a lot of

00:51:25.480 --> 00:51:31.080
[Guest]: firms got into trouble. Okay. And then we played that same story again, one more time. So in 2003,

00:51:31.080 --> 00:51:36.920
[Guest]: four, five, six, seven, we had the most gigantic investment boom in India's history. And then from

00:51:36.920 --> 00:51:43.880
[Guest]: 2011 onwards, we've been doing quite badly. Okay. And what's going on there is that there is a

00:51:43.880 --> 00:51:50.520
[Guest]: surge of entry and then competition hots up. And then what? If you do not think about exit of

00:51:50.520 --> 00:51:55.480
[Guest]: firms, if you do not think of firms closing down, firms getting sold, firms getting bought,

00:51:56.520 --> 00:52:02.360
[Guest]: then that misery just drags on for more years. Okay. So what we see in our business cycle

00:52:02.360 --> 00:52:08.920
[Guest]: research in India, so Radhika Pandey and Ela Patnaik and I have papers on measuring the

00:52:08.920 --> 00:52:14.040
[Guest]: Indian business cycle. And we are struck by how these things take more time in India. And we've

00:52:14.040 --> 00:52:19.800
[Guest]: often wondered what is going wrong. And when we compare with countries like the United States,

00:52:19.800 --> 00:52:25.560
[Guest]: it seems to us that one difference is that when things go wrong in the United States,

00:52:25.560 --> 00:52:30.280
[Guest]: they get rapidly cleaned up by the bankruptcy court. So people move fast. This isn't working,

00:52:31.000 --> 00:52:35.640
[Guest]: you get into trouble, you're down on your payments. I would also underline one more

00:52:35.640 --> 00:52:40.600
[Guest]: interesting feature here. All these things go faster when there is debt. Okay. So imagine I'm

00:52:40.600 --> 00:52:46.520
[Guest]: an all equity firm. I'm 100% equity. Now I can sustain my own bad behavior for some time. But

00:52:46.520 --> 00:52:52.040
[Guest]: when I have debt, I've got a Damocles sword on my head, I have to repay the debt. And when times

00:52:52.040 --> 00:52:58.200
[Guest]: become tough, when I'm unable to produce the cash, then I will fail on one of my debt repayments.

00:52:58.200 --> 00:53:02.280
[Guest]: And then you just want to go quickly, move it through the bankruptcy court, just go as quickly

00:53:02.280 --> 00:53:06.600
[Guest]: as you can to the bankruptcy court. Either the firm will be closed down, or it'll be sold to

00:53:06.600 --> 00:53:11.400
[Guest]: somebody else, very often an existing firm. So market power will develop that some of the

00:53:11.400 --> 00:53:16.200
[Guest]: survivors will achieve a little more clout in the market, be able to get the price up a little.

00:53:16.200 --> 00:53:20.280
[Guest]: And then profit rates will come back, investment will come back. So this whole cycle of life

00:53:21.320 --> 00:53:26.680
[Guest]: is playing out slowly in India, because we are prolonging the business of firm exit.

00:53:27.320 --> 00:53:32.760
[Amit Varma]: And how does the state contribute to that, for example, is, you know, the NPS problem

00:53:32.760 --> 00:53:38.120
[Amit Varma]: linked to that in the sense that bank or banks often keep these zombie firms alive by making

00:53:38.120 --> 00:53:42.440
[Amit Varma]: loans and then servicing those loans and keeping them alive and throwing good money after bad,

00:53:42.440 --> 00:53:47.640
[Guest]: and that prolongs the process. So this is very much a problem with our banking regulation.

00:53:47.640 --> 00:53:53.560
[Guest]: What should happen in banking regulation is, you see a borrower having distress,

00:53:53.560 --> 00:53:59.000
[Guest]: you must rapidly mark down the value of that asset. Okay, so imagine you gave me a loan of 100,

00:53:59.880 --> 00:54:02.680
[Guest]: you're supposed to be vigilant, you're the bank, you're supposed to be vigilant,

00:54:02.680 --> 00:54:06.520
[Guest]: you're supposed to watch me and understand my early signs of distress. Very often,

00:54:06.520 --> 00:54:10.600
[Guest]: you are my payments bank as well. So you're seeing my cash, you're seeing my revenues,

00:54:10.600 --> 00:54:14.680
[Guest]: you very much know when my life is not going so well. And of course, there is beautiful

00:54:14.680 --> 00:54:19.320
[Guest]: information in the accounting data, we can construct models of firm failure using the

00:54:19.320 --> 00:54:23.160
[Guest]: accounting data. So put it together, it's not difficult for a bank to know when the

00:54:23.160 --> 00:54:28.520
[Guest]: borrower is in trouble. Now the bank is supposed to make an estimate of what is the prospective

00:54:28.520 --> 00:54:34.440
[Guest]: market value of that loan, that if you try to take your loan to me and sell it to somebody else,

00:54:34.440 --> 00:54:39.160
[Guest]: what would that somebody else be willing to pay? What banking regulation has to do is to force

00:54:39.160 --> 00:54:44.840
[Guest]: banks to recognize these losses. So if the fair value of the loan on the market is going to go

00:54:44.840 --> 00:54:50.200
[Guest]: down from 100 to 60, then honestly, if I tried to sell this loan, the market would pay me 60,

00:54:50.200 --> 00:54:54.760
[Guest]: then the bank should show that loss of 40 right now, because you've really lost that money.

00:54:54.760 --> 00:55:00.200
[Guest]: And you should show it right now. Now, as you will expect, no bank employee wants to do that.

00:55:00.200 --> 00:55:05.320
[Guest]: So that's what banking regulation is all about. Banking regulation is about forcing bank employees

00:55:05.320 --> 00:55:10.600
[Guest]: to face up to the difficulties in their book and recognize these losses and take the losses

00:55:10.600 --> 00:55:17.240
[Guest]: on the chin. Now, we haven't particularly done that. So RBI has long had a history of being kind

00:55:17.240 --> 00:55:22.360
[Guest]: to banks, of being kind to the borrowers of banks. And so these things just slither on for years and

00:55:22.360 --> 00:55:31.560
[Guest]: years. So in our calculations, we believe that if the Indian debt crisis and the banking crisis

00:55:31.560 --> 00:55:41.880
[Guest]: had been dealt with in 2011, 2012, 2013, the cost of equity capital that was required inside Indian

00:55:41.880 --> 00:55:49.720
[Guest]: banking would have been about 2-3 trillion rupees. Every year of delay has driven up that cost.

00:55:49.720 --> 00:55:55.480
[Guest]: Today, it would cost 8 or 10 trillion rupees to fix all the banks. Because when you don't solve

00:55:55.480 --> 00:55:59.160
[Guest]: these things, they just become more and more expensive because you have to put more money

00:55:59.160 --> 00:56:05.080
[Guest]: after the old money. So these are the sorts of things where a society has to be organized

00:56:05.080 --> 00:56:11.560
[Guest]: around a philosophy of the market economy. We need all of us to come to grips with these concepts

00:56:11.560 --> 00:56:18.520
[Guest]: that when there is a loan, there will be a fairly tough bankruptcy code in it. And the bank will

00:56:18.520 --> 00:56:23.000
[Guest]: recognize these losses fairly quickly and so on. When a bank doesn't work, we will close down a

00:56:23.000 --> 00:56:29.720
[Guest]: bank. These are all the concepts of a market economy, the discipline, the rigor of a market economy.

00:56:29.720 --> 00:56:34.120
[Guest]: And I think we're just at the early stages of learning how these institutional things work.

00:56:34.120 --> 00:56:37.960
[Amit Varma]: And like you said, the incentive of a politician who's always fixed on the short term and always

00:56:37.960 --> 00:56:41.960
[Amit Varma]: fixed on the next election will always be to kick the can down the road. You know, bureaucrats will

00:56:41.960 --> 00:56:47.960
[Amit Varma]: have the same inclination. And even bankers, for example, will not want to take the, you know,

00:56:47.960 --> 00:56:51.720
[Amit Varma]: there is policy paralysis when they're worried that okay, if I give a haircut on this loan,

00:56:51.720 --> 00:56:56.360
[Amit Varma]: if I take a haircut on this loan, I could be accused of corruption. And all of those factors

00:56:56.360 --> 00:57:00.040
[Guest]: and those different incentives. We need to solve some of these things. So for example,

00:57:00.680 --> 00:57:05.720
[Guest]: a banker being held responsible when there is a markdown on the loan, we have to build

00:57:06.280 --> 00:57:14.440
[Guest]: the institutions, the machinery to protect people to find ways of determining what is the size of

00:57:14.440 --> 00:57:22.280
[Guest]: the damage and so on. But this is the puzzle that we face that how do we create a society where

00:57:22.280 --> 00:57:27.720
[Guest]: there is creative destruction. All the things we talked about fit under that puzzle that we need to

00:57:27.720 --> 00:57:33.160
[Guest]: get entrepreneurs and employees used to the idea that firms come and firms go. We need to get

00:57:33.160 --> 00:57:41.240
[Guest]: banks used to the idea that they will mark down the losses that have occurred and that sometimes

00:57:41.240 --> 00:57:47.080
[Guest]: banks will go bust. We need a banking regulation capacity that will hawkishly monitor banks and

00:57:47.080 --> 00:57:51.240
[Guest]: make sure that they do these things correctly. And in return is this very big prize. And that

00:57:51.240 --> 00:57:56.440
[Guest]: very big prize is that we will finish off with downturns quickly. And it seems to me like a very

00:57:56.440 --> 00:58:00.840
[Guest]: big prize that it would be a truly great thing for a country that you go through a great investment

00:58:00.840 --> 00:58:06.200
[Guest]: boom, then there is really tough competition within a short time, maybe one year, two years,

00:58:06.200 --> 00:58:10.840
[Guest]: you work it out, and then you restart the next big boom. Whereas in India, these things slide

00:58:10.840 --> 00:58:15.240
[Amit Varma]: down for many, many years. So, you know, before we end the episode, I'd also then like you to,

00:58:15.240 --> 00:58:20.600
[Amit Varma]: I mean, elaborate on GST. You were obviously, as you mentioned, in the early days involved with

00:58:20.600 --> 00:58:26.200
[Amit Varma]: designing the GST and what eventually got implemented by the Modi government is much more

00:58:26.200 --> 00:58:33.160
[Amit Varma]: convoluted than people like you would have liked. And your case was that a good GST, a simple GST

00:58:33.160 --> 00:58:38.760
[Amit Varma]: with one low tax with a good administrative structure would have helped kill off zombie

00:58:38.760 --> 00:58:44.520
[Guest]: firms faster. Explain that process to me. What is happening in India is that we have too many

00:58:44.520 --> 00:58:51.240
[Guest]: different rates. And it's become complicated, you could be an inefficient firm and take cover in

00:58:51.240 --> 00:58:58.200
[Guest]: various clauses of the tax code, or you could take cover in tax evasion. So the sophisticated idea is

00:58:58.200 --> 00:59:06.360
[Guest]: that the low productivity firms of India are hiding in violating regulations, in emitting

00:59:06.360 --> 00:59:14.120
[Guest]: pollution when that should not be done, and in cheating on taxes. So the deep insight is that

00:59:14.120 --> 00:59:23.000
[Guest]: if we are able to build a simple clean GST, again, my idea is very clear about 8-10% single rate on

00:59:23.000 --> 00:59:30.840
[Guest]: single rate on everything, just a universal base, 8%, 10% on everything, a simple tax administration,

00:59:30.840 --> 00:59:36.600
[Guest]: then a lot of the hassle is taken out. And the room for fudging around is taken out,

00:59:36.600 --> 00:59:42.520
[Guest]: the room for discretion by the tax authorities taken out. And what that will do is it will

00:59:42.520 --> 00:59:48.440
[Guest]: uncover the inefficient firms, the zombie firms, the low productivity firms that have been hiding

00:59:48.440 --> 00:59:56.120
[Guest]: in the woodwork based on their ability to cheat on taxes. So big phenomenon we see in India is that

00:59:56.120 --> 01:00:04.280
[Guest]: we see large, sophisticated, high technology firms often tend to have a high compliance culture.

01:00:04.280 --> 01:00:12.200
[Guest]: They meet every pollution regulation, they meet every labour law, they meet every tax requirement.

01:00:12.200 --> 01:00:16.040
[Guest]: And that's great. We want those kinds of firms to thrive. But those firms don't really make

01:00:16.040 --> 01:00:20.520
[Guest]: the kind of profit margins they ought to, because they're competing with a low productivity firm

01:00:20.520 --> 01:00:26.200
[Guest]: that manages to cheat on regulation, to cheat on pollution, to cheat on labour law, to cheat

01:00:26.200 --> 01:00:31.640
[Guest]: on taxation. So that's the big idea about the connection between GST and zombie firms.

01:00:31.640 --> 01:00:35.720
[Amit Varma]: And what you also pointed out was that before the GST came into play, and to some extent,

01:00:35.720 --> 01:00:40.520
[Amit Varma]: maybe still now, is that you had taxation of transactions, which in public finance called

01:00:40.520 --> 01:00:46.440
[Amit Varma]: bad taxes. And then what that forces companies to do is it creates an incentive towards vertical

01:00:46.440 --> 01:00:53.400
[Amit Varma]: integration. The example you gave was that let's say if you are, you know, taxing, you know, when

01:00:53.400 --> 01:00:57.640
[Amit Varma]: the engine of a car is made, and then when the car is put together, and if you're taxing them

01:00:57.640 --> 01:01:01.880
[Amit Varma]: separately, then it's in a company's interest to bring it all in house in this vertical integration.

01:01:01.880 --> 01:01:08.120
[Amit Varma]: Whereas economies advance, the more there is specialization. And, you know, not having not

01:01:08.120 --> 01:01:14.200
[Amit Varma]: taxing each transaction separately, and a GST basically treats them all as one reduces the

01:01:14.200 --> 01:01:18.520
[Amit Varma]: incentive for vertical integration, you have more specialization, and everybody benefits.

01:01:18.520 --> 01:01:25.000
[Guest]: So this is the old Adam Smith idea, that we each of us specialize, and we get to doing something

01:01:25.000 --> 01:01:31.080
[Guest]: very well. And that leads to a very nice intuition in a market economy, that a sophisticated economy

01:01:31.080 --> 01:01:38.040
[Guest]: is one in which we transact more. Okay, so more turnover is the hallmark of a more sophisticated

01:01:38.040 --> 01:01:42.840
[Guest]: economy. So we are arm's length firms, you are an engine producer, I am a car producer.

01:01:43.480 --> 01:01:47.800
[Guest]: But we still do a lot of business with each other separately, because I'm buying

01:01:47.800 --> 01:01:52.840
[Guest]: your engine. Whereas in a less sophisticated economy, we vertically integrate these things

01:01:52.840 --> 01:01:59.960
[Guest]: into vertically integrated monoliths. And this is a less efficient way of organizing society.

01:01:59.960 --> 01:02:05.880
[Guest]: So it's a very simple public finance idea that never tax transactions. A transaction tax is

01:02:05.880 --> 01:02:10.920
[Guest]: always a bad tax. Because that way you are interfering with the very lifeblood of an

01:02:10.920 --> 01:02:14.120
[Guest]: efficient society, which is many, many people doing many, many trades.

01:02:15.000 --> 01:02:19.960
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, to end the episode, a final question, you know, you've worked for a couple

01:02:19.960 --> 01:02:24.680
[Amit Varma]: of decades now, you know, in public policy, you worked within government, you worked with the

01:02:24.680 --> 01:02:28.360
[Amit Varma]: Ministry of Finance, do you see the thinking on this changing? Like, obviously, it's a good thing

01:02:28.360 --> 01:02:32.360
[Amit Varma]: that JET was allowed to close down. But do you broadly see the thinking on this changing that

01:02:32.360 --> 01:02:37.480
[Amit Varma]: we have a GST, even if it's not a perfect one? We have the IBC, even if it's not being implemented

01:02:37.480 --> 01:02:45.240
[Guest]: perfectly? Do you see the mindset changing? I'm actually a little disappointed. So I started

01:02:45.240 --> 01:02:53.000
[Guest]: out in India in 1993. And there was a lot of excitement about the market economy. And I felt

01:02:53.000 --> 01:02:57.640
[Guest]: many people were very self consciously trying to understand what it means to live in a market

01:02:57.640 --> 01:03:04.760
[Guest]: economy, and to adapt oneself and one's organisation into the concepts and frameworks of a

01:03:04.760 --> 01:03:11.960
[Guest]: market economy. I think some of that intellectual construct has gone astray. And we are losing

01:03:11.960 --> 01:03:17.480
[Guest]: sight of the foundations, we are losing a sense of the fundamentals. So I feel, in some ways,

01:03:17.480 --> 01:03:25.160
[Guest]: we are less equipped in terms of the worldview and the framework today than we were in 1993.

01:03:25.160 --> 01:03:29.320
[Guest]: And it's a bit of a disappointment that this hasn't quite gone as I had hoped it would go.

01:03:29.320 --> 01:03:31.160
[Amit Varma]: This is a policy universe you're talking about?

01:03:31.160 --> 01:03:35.880
[Guest]: This is the mind of all of us about how we think about markets, how we think about government,

01:03:35.880 --> 01:03:37.240
[Guest]: how we think about the role of state.

01:03:38.200 --> 01:03:42.360
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting because 60% of India is born after liberalisation, right? So you would

01:03:42.360 --> 01:03:47.960
[Amit Varma]: not expect these kind of reflexive worship of the state to sort of be there.

01:03:47.960 --> 01:03:50.280
[Guest]: I think a reflexive socialism is alive and well.

01:03:50.280 --> 01:03:55.000
[Amit Varma]: On that extremely hopeful note, Ajay, thank you so much for coming on the show.

01:03:55.000 --> 01:04:22.520
[Amit Varma]: My pleasure.

01:04:25.000 --> 01:04:50.200
[Amit Varma]: Advertising is dead. Yep, you heard me right. Advertising is dead.

01:04:50.200 --> 01:04:55.640
[Unknown]: We're all in the content business now. Let's not call it news, TV, radio, etc, etc. It's all content

01:04:55.640 --> 01:04:59.720
[Unknown]: and we're in the middle of this weirdly exciting phase where all the borders and lines that have

01:04:59.720 --> 01:05:03.880
[Unknown]: been drawn over decades has been swept away by this lovely thing called the internet.

01:05:03.880 --> 01:05:07.320
[Unknown]: We're a show where we don't dwell on just the stuff that is now, but rather the wider stuff

01:05:07.320 --> 01:05:10.920
[Unknown]: about advertising, media, content and the whole goddamn circus surrounding it.

01:05:10.920 --> 01:05:16.040
[Unknown]: Tune in every Tuesday for a weekly unboxing of the mystery box we used to call advertising.

01:05:16.040 --> 01:05:20.520
[Unknown]: I'm Varun Duggirala, co-founder and content chief at The Gritch, and this is my new podcast.

01:05:20.520 --> 01:05:48.040
[Unknown]: Advertising is dead.

